00:00:59.380 --> 00:01:05.489
So let's start with a review of
the supply and demand framework

00:01:05.489 --> 00:01:07.900
that we introduced
in the first lecture.

00:01:07.900 --> 00:01:10.750
So let's go back to figure 9-1.

00:01:10.750 --> 00:01:14.130
We've got the market
for gasoline, OK?

00:01:14.130 --> 00:01:16.670
On the x-axis is big
Q. Quantity of gas

00:01:16.670 --> 00:01:18.720
is the market-level diagram.

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:21.120
On the y-axis--
the price of gas.

00:01:21.120 --> 00:01:23.310
And as we said, the first
lecture-- the supply curve

00:01:23.310 --> 00:01:25.830
that's upward sloping,
representing the fact

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:28.440
that higher prices
call forth more supply.

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:30.490
We now know where
that comes from.

00:01:30.490 --> 00:01:33.420
We know that what happens is
when there's a higher price,

00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:37.800
firms can now afford to move up
the marginal cost curve, which

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:39.060
is the supply curve.

00:01:39.060 --> 00:01:40.590
So we know where
that comes from.

00:01:40.590 --> 00:01:43.320
We have demand curve,
which is downward sloping.

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:44.820
Higher prices lead
to less demand.

00:01:44.820 --> 00:01:46.540
We know where that comes from.

00:01:46.540 --> 00:01:48.960
We know that as the
price of a good rises,

00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:50.550
through both income
and substitution

00:01:50.550 --> 00:01:54.210
effects for normal goods,
consumers will want less of it,

00:01:54.210 --> 00:01:55.810
so whenever that comes from.

00:01:55.810 --> 00:01:57.090
So we now have derived these.

00:01:57.090 --> 00:01:59.560
And we're back where we
started in equilibrium.

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:03.400
So let's actually start
by asking what happens.

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:05.980
Let's start by asking,
as we move forward,

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:07.920
how do we want to think
about these curves?

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:08.910
And the way we
think about them is

00:02:08.910 --> 00:02:10.820
we want to think about
the demand curve,

00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:12.720
want to think about
these as willingness

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:16.240
to pay and willingness
to supply curves.

00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:19.710
So think about the demand curve
as a willingness to pay curve.

00:02:19.710 --> 00:02:22.415
How much are you
willing to pay to get

00:02:22.415 --> 00:02:23.540
that next unit of the good?

00:02:23.540 --> 00:02:26.430
Or how much is the market
willing to pay to get

00:02:26.430 --> 00:02:28.250
the next unit of the good?

00:02:28.250 --> 00:02:29.370
OK?

00:02:29.370 --> 00:02:33.020
And the supply curve is
willing to supply, OK?

00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:37.020
An equilibrium is the point
where consumers' willingness

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:40.080
to pay for the next
unit of the good

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:42.070
meets the suppliers
willing to supply

00:02:42.070 --> 00:02:43.970
the next unit of the good.

00:02:43.970 --> 00:02:46.080
When those are equal,
we're in equilibrium.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.610
So that's where we start.

00:02:49.610 --> 00:02:53.570
Now, let's ask, what happens
as these curves shift?

00:02:53.570 --> 00:02:56.000
So, for example,
let's take this market

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.010
and imagine the tastes change.

00:02:58.010 --> 00:03:00.830
Suddenly, everyone
wants to drive big cars.

00:03:00.830 --> 00:03:03.318
Everyone wants to
drive SUVs, OK?

00:03:03.318 --> 00:03:04.985
What does this do to
the market for gas?

00:03:07.670 --> 00:03:09.090
Well, so what does this do?

00:03:09.090 --> 00:03:11.278
Well, what it does--
yeah, go ahead.

00:03:11.278 --> 00:03:13.070
AUDIENCE: SUVs require
a lot more gasoline,

00:03:13.070 --> 00:03:14.390
so the demand goes up.

00:03:14.390 --> 00:03:15.380
JONATHAN GRUBER: Yes.

00:03:15.380 --> 00:03:21.200
SUVs are what we call
a complement as opposed

00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:22.990
to substitute--

00:03:22.990 --> 00:03:25.400
are a complement for gasoline.

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:27.980
When demand for SUVs goes
up, demand for gas goes up.

00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:30.210
So the demand curve
would shift out.

00:03:30.210 --> 00:03:35.120
So we would end up in a
situation like figure 9-2.

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:37.280
But let's talk
through the dynamics.

00:03:37.280 --> 00:03:41.510
All you would see in the
market is quantity of gas sold

00:03:41.510 --> 00:03:44.390
would go up from Q1 to Q2.

00:03:44.390 --> 00:03:47.110
And price of gas would
go up from P1 to P2.

00:03:47.110 --> 00:03:49.580
Well, let's talk about
underneath, how we get there.

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:51.763
What happens is
demand shifts up.

00:03:51.763 --> 00:03:53.180
People want more
gas, because they

00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:55.280
want to drive these
gas-guzzling cars.

00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:58.850
So demand shifts from D1 to D2.

00:03:58.850 --> 00:04:00.330
What does that mean?

00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:04.580
That means at the previous
equilibrium price--

00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:07.490
if the price didn't
change, if the price

00:04:07.490 --> 00:04:09.980
stayed a P1, what would happen?

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:12.290
Well, we'd no longer
be in equilibrium.

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:14.720
Because people would--
firms would still

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:18.230
be happy to supply
Q1 units of gas.

00:04:18.230 --> 00:04:20.690
But people would want
way more than that.

00:04:20.690 --> 00:04:23.030
We would have excess demand.

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:25.790
If the price didn't change,
there would be excess demand.

00:04:25.790 --> 00:04:31.150
People would want more
than the Q1 units of gas.

00:04:31.150 --> 00:04:33.710
Suppliers will recognize
this and say, well,

00:04:33.710 --> 00:04:37.070
if people want more, we're
happy to produce more.

00:04:37.070 --> 00:04:39.700
But remember, we have to
respect the marginal cost curve

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:41.128
and marginal cost of rising.

00:04:41.128 --> 00:04:42.670
If we're going to
produce more, we're

00:04:42.670 --> 00:04:44.140
going to have to charge more.

00:04:44.140 --> 00:04:47.110
We're going to have to
move up the supply curve.

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:51.430
So a shift in the demand
curve makes firms move along

00:04:51.430 --> 00:04:52.480
the supply curve.

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:55.030
Want to keep shifts and
movement along curves separate.

00:04:55.030 --> 00:04:58.020
A shift in demand
curve, meaning people

00:04:58.020 --> 00:05:00.380
are saying to gas
producers, we want more gas.

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:01.630
Gas producers are like, great.

00:05:01.630 --> 00:05:02.980
We want to give you more
gas, but we're going

00:05:02.980 --> 00:05:04.510
to charge you more to do it.

00:05:04.510 --> 00:05:07.150
Because our marginal cost
curve is upward sloping,

00:05:07.150 --> 00:05:08.980
which is our supply
curve, as we learned.

00:05:08.980 --> 00:05:10.660
So the price rises.

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:15.030
And we need to reach a
new equilibrium at E2.

00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:18.092
So we don't see these
steps in practice.

00:05:18.092 --> 00:05:19.800
In the end, we just
see the price change,

00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:21.600
but think about it as two steps.

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:24.840
Demand shifts out,
creating excess demand.

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:28.130
Providers, to meet that excess
demand, have to produce more.

00:05:28.130 --> 00:05:30.630
And to produce more, they're
going to charge a higher price.

00:05:30.630 --> 00:05:33.710
And that moves you
from E1 to E2, OK?

00:05:33.710 --> 00:05:36.320
So we have a shift in
demand, which caused a slide

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:39.870
up the supply curve, OK?

00:05:39.870 --> 00:05:41.880
Now, let's think about
a different example.

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:43.890
Imagine war breaks out
in the Middle East.

00:05:43.890 --> 00:05:46.530
Not too hard to
imagine, unfortunately.

00:05:46.530 --> 00:05:49.440
And as a result, the quantity--

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:54.570
so suppliers need to pay
more to get the oil that they

00:05:54.570 --> 00:05:57.030
use to make gasoline, OK?

00:05:57.030 --> 00:05:58.110
What does that do?

00:05:58.110 --> 00:06:01.110
We see that in figure 9-3.

00:06:01.110 --> 00:06:07.490
Now, what happens is
for every unit of gas,

00:06:07.490 --> 00:06:09.230
suppliers need to charge more.

00:06:09.230 --> 00:06:12.695
Their underlying marginal
costs have gone up,

00:06:12.695 --> 00:06:14.570
because they have to
pay more to get the oil.

00:06:14.570 --> 00:06:16.880
That's a variable cost
of production of gas.

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:19.022
So their marginal
costs have gone up.

00:06:19.022 --> 00:06:21.230
Their marginal costs going
up mean their supply curve

00:06:21.230 --> 00:06:23.420
has shifted upwards, OK?

00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:27.150
For every unit of production,
their marginal cost

00:06:27.150 --> 00:06:29.975
is higher, because their
variable costs have gone up.

00:06:29.975 --> 00:06:32.100
Therefore, they're going
to need to charge a higher

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:34.780
price to break even.

00:06:34.780 --> 00:06:36.780
OK, we're still in perfectly
competitive markets

00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:39.420
where nobody is
making any profit, OK?

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:41.470
They're going to charge
more to break even.

00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:43.470
So now, let's once again
talk about the dynamics

00:06:43.470 --> 00:06:45.280
of what's happening.

00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:48.160
The dynamics are the
costs and the input

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:50.230
to the suppliers went up--

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:52.390
oil, OK?

00:06:52.390 --> 00:06:55.810
Their marginal costs
shifts up to S2.

00:06:55.810 --> 00:06:58.190
So they want to
charge a higher price.

00:06:58.190 --> 00:07:01.150
So if we kept the
price the same as it

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:02.980
was before, suppliers
would say, we

00:07:02.980 --> 00:07:04.920
don't want to sell Q1 anymore.

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:08.330
We're not interested in selling
Q1 anymore at that old price.

00:07:08.330 --> 00:07:08.830
OK?

00:07:08.830 --> 00:07:10.540
That doesn't interest us.

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:14.080
Therefore, consumers
want more than providers

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:15.280
are willing to sell.

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:18.600
And we once again
have excess demand.

00:07:18.600 --> 00:07:21.910
So in both cases, we
get excess demand.

00:07:21.910 --> 00:07:24.110
In the first case,
we got excess demand

00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:26.120
because consumers wanted more.

00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:28.100
The lower-- the
consumers' tastes

00:07:28.100 --> 00:07:30.800
shifted, so they wanted
more gas at every price.

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:33.200
Now, we have excess demand
not because taste shift,

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:34.433
but because costs go up.

00:07:34.433 --> 00:07:36.350
So providers don't want
to provide as much gas

00:07:36.350 --> 00:07:38.490
at every price.

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:40.550
So what happens is
providers are going to say,

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:44.180
fine, we're going to
charge a higher price, OK?

00:07:44.180 --> 00:07:46.820
And we'll slide up
the demand curve.

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:48.710
Because as providers
charge a higher price,

00:07:48.710 --> 00:07:50.870
people want less gas.

00:07:50.870 --> 00:07:52.370
At a higher price,
you want less gas

00:07:52.370 --> 00:07:53.810
through the substitution effect.

00:07:53.810 --> 00:07:56.390
Because you'll buy other things
instead and for the income

00:07:56.390 --> 00:07:56.690
effect.

00:07:56.690 --> 00:07:58.107
Because you're
effectively poorer,

00:07:58.107 --> 00:07:59.860
because the price
of gas went up.

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:03.940
For those reasons, you're going
to shift up the demand curve

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:06.570
and reach a new
equilibrium at E2.

00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:08.670
So that's the
underlying dynamics

00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:10.740
of how shifts in
supply and demand

00:08:10.740 --> 00:08:15.060
lead to changes in
quantity and price, OK?

00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:17.490
So that's basically
what we're seeing.

00:08:17.490 --> 00:08:19.620
Questions about that?

